{
  "doc_id": "55326",
  "text": "Cardiovascular disease (CVD) is the leading cause of death in the U.S. and although CVD is a complex multi factorial disease, it is considered by some a postprandial phenomenon [CITATION_1] . Obesity is an independent risk factor for (CVD) [CITATION_2] , which is partially attributed to abnormalities in postprandial triacylglycerol (TAG) metabolism [CITATION_3] . Exaggerated and prolonged elevations in postprandial TAG concentrations directly contribute to both the atherosclerotic [CITATION_4] and thrombotic [CITATION_5] processes of CVD. In addition, exaggerated postprandial TAG concentrations result in decreased plasma high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL-C) concentrations [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . As low HDL-C concentrations are a risk factor for CVD [CITATION_9] , the postprandial decrease in HDL-C concentrations may contribute to the enhanced CVD risk associated with abnormally elevated postprandial TAG in obese individuals [CITATION_10] .",
